{
  "texts": [
    "As an intermediate step, we next move to the difference between the two policies π ⋆ p (λ ⋆ p) and π ⋆ (λ ⋆ p).",
    "To analyze it, we define two perturbations for any λ ≥ 0:ϵ ⋆ (λ):= E x E y ∼ π ⋆ (λ) [ h(x, y)] and ϵ ⋆ p (λ):= E x E y ∼ π ⋆ p (λ) [ h(x, y)] and a perturbation function for Problem (U-CA):P ⋆ (ϵ):= maximize π ∈ Π E x [ E y ∼ π [ r(x, y)] -β E x [ D KL (π(• | x) ∥ π ref (• | x))] (10)subject to E x [ E y ∼ π [ h i (x, y)]] ≥ ϵ i, for all i = 1,..., m.It is straightforward that P ⋆ (ϵ) is a concave function.",
    "To facilitate the sensitivity analysis, we assume the perturbed problem (10) is feasible, which is a special case of of Assumption 2.",
    "Assumption 6 (Strict feasibility).",
    "There exists a policy π ∈ Π such thatE x [ E y ∼ π [ h i (x, y)]] > max 0, ϵ ⋆ (λ ⋆ p), ϵ ⋆ p (λ ⋆ p), ϵ ⋆ p (λ ⋆) for all i = 1,..., m and for all λ ⋆ p ∈ argmin λ ≥ 0 D p (λ).Denote E:= {ϵ ∈ R m | ϵ:= γϵ ⋆ (λ ⋆ p) + (1 -γ)ϵ ⋆ p (λ ⋆ p), γ ∈ [0, 1]}.With Assumption 6, P ⋆ (ϵ) is always finite for any ϵ ∈ E. It is also known that P ⋆ (ϵ) is upper semi-continuous for strictly feasible problems [4]."
